# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1816-united-states-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The **15th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] It met in the Old Brick Capitol in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1817, to March 4, 1819, during the first two years of James Monroe's presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1810 United States census.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Two major treaties with the United Kingdom were approved, finalized and signed during the 15th Congress, both the Rush–Bagot Treaty and the Treaty of 1818, both of which pertained to the United States-Canada border, and both of which were overwhelmingly popular in the United States.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] President James Monroe and Secretary of State John Quincy Adams were credited with the accomplishments.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The letter also attacked King Louis XVIII of France for insulting remarks he had made towards American diplomats and about the United States, as well as his refusal to pay reparations owed to the United States from damages incurred during the Quasi-War.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The letter was signed in December 1818 by Joel Abbot, Thomas W.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Hall, Jesse Slocumb, James Owen, Weldon Nathaniel Edwards, James Stewart, James Strudwick Smith, Thomas Settle, George Mumford, Daniel Munroe Forney, Felix Walker, Lewis Williams, John J.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Marr, George Poindexter, Prentiss Mellen, Harrison Gray Otis, Enoch Lincoln, Jonathan Mason, Nathaniel Silsbee, Jeremiah Nelson, Timothy Fuller, Elijah H.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Several governors also signed the letter, which was entirely symbolic and intended as a gesture of goodwill, including Gabriel Slaughter, William Rabun, John Geddes, John Branch, John Brooks, James Patton Preston and David Holmes.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] This was significant because the governors and the members of congress were from different regions (both Massachusetts and several southern states were represented), and because signers came from both the Whig Party and the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Many members of congress and Washington DC had a very hostile relationship with France's notoriously combative ambassador Jean-Guillaume, baron Hyde de Neuville, which contributed to the letters contents as per France.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two Senate seats were added for each of the new states of Mississippi and Illinois.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one House seat was added for each of the new states of Mississippi and Illinois.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1820; Class 2 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1822; and Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1818.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/15th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] The first midterm elections were held in the United States in 1790 and 1791.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] They occurred in the middle of President George Washington's first term, and determined the members of the 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Formal political parties did not exist, but Congress was broadly divided between a faction supporting the policies of the Washington administration and a faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Despite modest gains for the anti-administration faction, the pro-administration faction retained control of both houses of Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Vermont and Kentucky joined the union during the 2nd Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the House, neither faction made significant gains or losses, and the pro-administration faction retained control of the chamber.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the anti-administration faction picked up a moderate number of seats, but the pro-administration faction narrowly retained control of the chamber.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 3rd United States Congress, in 1792 and 1793.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Congress was broadly divided between a Pro-Administration faction supporting the policies of George Washington's administration and an Anti-Administration faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Due to this, the Federalist Party (generally overlapping with the Pro-Administration faction) and the Democratic-Republican Party (generally overlapping with the Anti-Administration faction) were starting to emerge as the distinct political parties of the First Party System.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In this election, the Pro-Administration faction maintained control of the Senate, but lost its majority in the House.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, incumbent President George Washington was re-elected without any major opposition.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington had considered retirement, but was convinced to seek re-election for the purpose of national unity.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Though Washington went unchallenged, Governor George Clinton of New York sought to unseat John Adams as vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Adams received the second most electoral votes, and so was re-elected to office.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the House, 37 seats were added following the 1790 census.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction picked up several seats, narrowly taking the majority from the Pro-Administration faction.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Frederick Muhlenberg, who leaned closer to the Pro-Administration faction, was elected Speaker of the House.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Anti-Administration faction picked up one seat, but the Pro-Administration faction maintained a small majority.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Elections occurred in the middle of President George Washington's second term.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Members of the 4th United States Congress were chosen in this election.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Tennessee was admitted as a state during the 4th Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] The election took place at the beginning of the First Party System, with the Democratic-Republican Party and Federalist Party emerging as political parties, succeeding the anti-administration faction and the pro-administration faction.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the House, the Democratic-Republicans picked up a small number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] However, Federalist Jonathan Dayton was elected Speaker of the House, defeating Frederick Muhlenberg, who had a less clear partisan affiliation.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Federalists picked up a moderate number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 5th United States Congress, in 1796 and 1797.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The election took place during the beginning stages of the First Party System, as the Federalist Party and the Democratic-Republican Party clashed over the states' rights, the financial policies of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton, and the recently ratified Jay Treaty.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The Federalists maintained control of the Senate, and won control of the House and the presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the first contested presidential election and the first presidential election in which parties played a major role, Federalist Vice President John Adams narrowly defeated Democratic-Republican former Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams won New England while Jefferson won the South, leaving the mid-Atlantic states to decide the election.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] As the election took place prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, Jefferson, who finished with the second most electoral votes, succeeded Adams as vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Federalist former Governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina finished with the third most electoral votes, while Democratic-Republican Senator Aaron Burr of New York finished in fourth place.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] This election marked the only time in American history that members of two different political parties were elected as president and vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams's election made him the first member of a political party to be elected president, as George Washington had remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the House, Federalists won moderate gains, taking majority control of the chamber.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the Senate, Federalists picked up one seat, maintaining a commanding majority in the chamber.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] Elections to the 6th United States Congress were held in 1798 and 1799, during the middle of Federalist President John Adams's term.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] The election took place during the First Party System, as political competition between the Federalists and the Democratic-Republicans became increasingly organized.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] Federalists retained control of both chambers of Congress, gaining three seats in the House of Representatives while partisan balance of the Senate remained unchanged.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] The elections occurred amid growing tensions between the United States and France.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] Federalists generally favored a stronger central government and closer commercial relations with Great Britain, while Democratic-Republicans favored a more limited federal government and were more sympathetic to France.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] In April 1798, the Adams administration released dispatches describing the XYZ Affair, in which French intermediaries had demanded payments from American diplomats seeking negotiations with the French government.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] Public outrage over the affair contributed to heightened anti-French sentiment, and the dispute developed into the undeclared naval conflict known as the Quasi-War.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] During the same period, the Federalist-controlled 5th Congress enacted the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] The laws increased the residency requirement for citizenship, authorized federal action against certain non-citizens, and criminalized some forms of criticism of the federal government.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] They became a major source of partisan controversy and were primarily enforced against supporters and newspaper editors associated with the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] All 106 voting seats in the House were contested.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] The Federalists gained three seats, increasing their majority from 57-49 in the 5th Congress to 60-46 in the 6th Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] Federalist Representative Theodore Sedgwick of Massachusetts was subsequently elected speaker of the House.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] Eleven of the Senate's 32 seats were scheduled for regular election.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1798-united-states-elections] The elections produced no net partisan change, leaving the Federalists with 22 seats and the Democratic-Republicans with 10.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] Elections for the 15th United States Congress were held in 1816 and 1817.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] Mississippi and Illinois were admitted as states during the 15th Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] The election took place during the First Party System.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] The Democratic-Republican Party controlled the presidency and both houses of Congress, while the Federalist Party provided only limited opposition.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] The election marked the start of the Era of Good Feelings, as the Federalist Party became nearly irrelevant in national politics after the War of 1812 and the Hartford Convention.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, Democratic-Republican Secretary of State James Monroe easily defeated Federalist Senator Rufus King of New York.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] Monroe faced a more difficult challenge in securing his party's nomination, but was able to defeat Secretary of War William H.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] Crawford in the Democratic-Republican congressional nominating caucus.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] The Federalists never again fielded a presidential candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] In the House, Democratic-Republicans won major gains, and continued to dominate the chamber.
[src:1816-united-states-elections/1816-united-states-elections] In the Senate, Democratic-Republicans picked up a moderate number of seats, increasing their already-dominant majority.
